On March 2, 2026, the A-share market exhibited extreme divergence, influenced by escalating Middle East geopolitical conflict and central bank policy adjustments. The Shanghai Composite Index rose 0.47% to 4182.59 points, while the Shenzhen Component and ChiNext indices fell, with turnover at a historically high 3.05 trillion yuan. The market identified three core investment themes: geopolitical hedging (oil & gas, precious metals, defense), policy beneficiaries (new energy vehicles, power grid equipment), and earnings certainty (consumer recovery, high dividends). Key variables to watch include Middle East developments, the upcoming National Two Sessions policy expectations, and corporate annual report verification.

In macro news, the People's Bank of China lowered the foreign exchange risk reserve ratio for forward sales from 20% to 0% starting March 2 to support corporate forex risk management. The 2025 GDP reached 140.19 trillion yuan, up 5.0% year-on-year. The U.S.-Israel military strike on Iran, resulting in the death of Supreme Leader Khamenei and the closure of the Strait of Hormuz, caused international oil prices to surge, with Brent crude up 13% to $82/barrel. Gold hit a record high above $5,300/ounce.

Industry news showed severe divergence: the oil & petrochemical sector surged nearly 6% with many stocks hitting limit-up, while the new energy sector, particularly photovoltaics, fell sharply due to high valuations, capital flight to safe havens, and overseas demand concerns. However, new energy vehicle subsidies were fully implemented nationwide, offering up to 20,000 yuan for replacements. In tech, OpenAI secured $110 billion in funding, and China's AI model weekly call volume surpassed the U.S. for the first time. Storage chip prices hit multi-year highs.

Institutional research reports indicated optimism. Everbright Securities recommended focusing on growth (humanoid robots, computers, AI) and cyclical sectors. CICC saw opportunities in lithium batteries due to demand recovery and solid-state battery progress. JPMorgan was bullish on Chinese stocks, predicting a 17% upside for the CSI 300, citing anti-internal competition policies and AI support. Analysts viewed the Iran conflict impact as a 'short-term pulse, medium-term differentiation.'
